\section{Introduction}
Following the discovery of the Standard Model (SM) Higgs boson~\cite{higgs_atlas, higgs_cms}, it is of more interest to search for new high-mass particles, such as additional Higgs bosons~\cite{hmhiggs_atlas1, hmhiggs_atlas2, hmhiggs_cms1, hmhiggs_cms2}. Recently, in the $\gamma\gamma$ mass spectrum, a resonance around the mass $750$~GeV/$c^2$ is seen with a significance of about $3\sigma$~\cite{h750_atlas, h750_cms}. In the SM and many beyond-SM theories, the coupling of the Higgs boson and the fermions is proportional to the mass of the fermion. For a neutral Higgs boson, $h^0$, the branching fraction of $h^0 \to\tau^+\tau^-$ would be dominant compared to other leptons $e$ and $\mu$. Experimentally, the presence of neutrinos makes it challenging to reconstruct the invariant mass $M(\tau\tau)$ accurately. Accordingly, the performance of mass reconstruction technique affects the sensitivity of probing new physics.

There are a few techniques of $M(\tau\tau)$ reconstruction that are commonly used in the hadron colliders. The study of these techniques can be found in Ref.~\cite{masscon_atlas, masscon_cms, MMC, SMR}. Here is a short summary. 
\begin{enumerate}
\item The Transverse Mass Method (TMM): $M(\tau\tau)=\sqrt{(P_{vis_1}+P_{vis_2}+P_{ME})^2}$. Here $P_{vis_1}$ and $P_{vis_2}$ are the 4-momenta of the visible decay products of the tau leptons; $P_{ME} \equiv (ME_x, ME_y, 0, \sqrt{ME_x^2+ME_y^2})$ with $ME_{x,y}$ being the $x,y$ component of the missing energy. This method assumes that only the neutrinos from the tau decays contribute to the missing transverse energy. We call it the ``missing transverse energy assumption'' ($MTEA$). Furthermore, it is not able to consider the $z$ component of the momentum of the missing neutrinos. The resulting $M(\tau\tau)$ spectrum is thus biased and broadened.  
\item The Collinear Approximation Technique (CAT): It is based on the $MTEA$. It also assumes that the neutrinos from each tau decay are collinear with the visible tau decay products, the charged leptons or the hadronical $\tau$ jets. Thus the 4-momenta of the neutrinos can be fully determined. $M(\tau\tau) = \sqrt{(P_{vis_1}+P_{vis_2})^2}/\sqrt{x_1x_2}$. $x_{1,2}$ are the momentum fractions carried by the visible tau decay products. The explicit expressions are written below.

nexttext:
\end{enumerate}

In this paper, we propose a method, which inherits the similar idea from the MMCT. But the method does not rely on the usage of the missing transverse energy and does not need to solve a set of equations. In Sec.~\ref{sec:principle}, we present the principle of this method. In Sec.~\ref{sec:performance}, the method is tested on the MC simulations. Different mass reconstruction techniques are compared in Sec.~\ref{sec:compare}. We give the conclusions in Sec.~\ref{sec:conclusion}.  

