\section{Comparison of different mass reconstruction techniques}~\label{sec:compare}
We only compare three techniques, namely CAT, MMCT and the one described in this work. Three quantites are used to measure the performance, namely, the reconstruction efficiency due to the technique itself, the relative mass resolution and the reconstruction speed. They are explained below. 

The reconstruction efficiency describes the rate of successful mass reconstruction. In the CAT, the mass can not be reasonably reconstructed if $x_{1,2}<0$ or $x_{1,2}>1$ in Eq.~\ref{eq:cat}. The efficiency is about 40\%-60\%. In the MMCT, the efficiency lose is only a few percents due to that the set of equations, shown in Eq.~\ref{eq:mmc}, can not be solved at some points in the parameter space. The technique in this work does not require to solve a set equation and thus has no efficiency lose.

The relative mass resolution is defined as the standard deviation within $\pm 40\%$ of the generated mass divided by the generated mass, denoted by $\sigma_M/M$, the same as that in Ref~\cite{MMC}. Both the MMCT and our technique give a similar relative mass resolution, about 14\%, which is better than that in the CAT. 

The reconstruction efficiency and the relative mass resolution are two crucial elements to search for new resonance and distinguish the resonance signal from the backgrounds. In reality, we also expect that a technique is able to work fast.  From this perspective, the method in this work seems better than the MMCT. The latter one involves the numerical solution of a set of nonlinear equations, which is usually time-consuming. Table~\ref{tab:compare} summarizes the performances of the three techniques.  

