\section{Conclusions}\label{sec:conclusion}
In summary, we propose a new technique to reconstruct the mass of a heavy resonance decaying to $\tau^+\tau^-$. The technique is based on the collinear approximation. It also inherits the idea from the MMCT, which is that the reconstructed mass is assumed to correspond to the point with the maximal probability in the parameter space. This method avoids the time-consuming numerical solution of a set of nonlinear equations and does not rely on the assumption that the missing transverse energy is due to the neutrinos from the tau leptons. By testing on the MC simulations of $pp\to Z/h(125)/h'(750)\to\tau^+\tau^-$, the method has an efficiency 100\% and gives a relative mass resolution about 14\%. It is found to have a better performance than the CAT and the MMCT. 

